est suitor. This study challenges an understanding of these women as passive recipients of social and spiritual influence by re-situating female authority within the context of vision, language, and performativity. Included in the study are transcriptions of twenty-two previously unedited lives. Emma Gatland is a Leverhulme Early Career Fellow, University of Cambridge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChristian hagiography. 0aSpanish literatureyTo 1500xHistory and criticism. 0aWomen saintsvBiography. 4aHispanic Studies. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aEurope.  aFemale Agency.  aFemale Saints.  aFemale authority.  aFeminism.  aGender studies.  aGender.  aGolden Legend.  aHagiography.  aMedieval Spanish literature.  aMedieval history.  aMedieval women.  aPagan.  aReligion.  aSaint.  aSanctoral.  aWomen's history.  aWomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846159985423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846159985/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles